Task:
Implement a Telegram teacher content editor flow centered around `/teacher_content`.

IMPORTANT:
- Use FSM only for transient UI/navigation state.
- Do NOT move domain truth into FSM.
- Do NOT redesign learner training.
- Do NOT introduce generic menu frameworks.
- Do NOT implement hard delete in this step.
- Keep callback payloads short and minimal.
- Keep all user-visible text in centralized i18n.
- Keep command registration centralized in `englishbot/command_registry.py`.

CRITICAL TELEGRAM UX RULES:
- Do not accumulate duplicate menu messages during `/teacher_content` navigation.
- Workspace list and topic list are single-screen menus and must be updated in place via message editing whenever possible.
- Entering “create workspace” or “create topic” must replace the current menu message with a compact prompt screen, not send a new menu copy.
- Prompt screens must show only:
  - one compact prompt text
  - one back button
- Pressing Back from a prompt must restore the previous menu in the same message.
- Use new `answer()` messages only when necessary:
  - for the dedicated 3-message topic editor screen
  - or as fallback when Telegram editing fails
- Topic editor may remain a 3-message screen by design, but prompt-like subflows inside it should prefer message replacement instead of piling up transient prompts.

Goal:
Turn `/teacher_content` from read-only browsing into a minimal but usable teacher-side content editor.

Scope:

1. Workspace level
- `/teacher_content` must allow the teacher to:
  - browse their teacher workspaces
  - create a new teacher workspace

2. Topic level
Inside a selected teacher workspace:
- browse topics
- create a new topic
- open a selected topic

3. Topic editor screen
Inside a selected topic, implement a 3-message UI model:

Message A: topic navigator
- show up to 25 item rows for the current page
- clearly mark the currently selected item
- support page navigation if topic has more than 25 items

Message B: current item image
- show current item image if present
- otherwise show a compact no-image placeholder
- support setting/replacing image through a dedicated button flow

Message C: current item card + actions
- show current item details:
  - headword/text
  - ru / uk / bg translations if present
  - image_ref / audio_ref compactly
  - archive status
- include navigation/actions:
  - previous item
  - next item
  - edit item
  - archive item
  - add item
  - back to topics
  - publish topic

4. Editing flow
Implement item editing through FSM-backed field editing.

FSM is allowed only for:
- selected workspace/topic/item ids
- current page
- which field is being edited
- message ids for screen restoration / the 3-message topic editor
- prompt message id when a menu screen is temporarily replaced

Do NOT store domain truth in FSM.

Field editing requirements:
- support editing:
  - item text/headword
  - ru translation
  - uk translation
  - bg translation
- missing translation tags are allowed at the data level
- adding a translation later must be supported naturally
- use one-field-at-a-time editing, not a free-form document editor
- after saving, refresh the 3-message screen

5. Item creation
- allow adding a new item inside the current topic
- minimal creation flow is enough:
  - create base item text
  - optionally add translations afterward through the same field-edit flow

6. Image flow
- from the item screen, allow “set image”
- bot then waits for a photo/message relevant to image input
- update `image_ref` using the project’s existing local asset-reference approach if compatible
- if full asset persistence is not yet implemented for uploaded Telegram files, keep the flow minimal and explicit instead of faking support

7. Publish
- from topic screen, allow explicit publish action
- reuse existing publish/topic-access logic where possible
- do not duplicate domain logic

8. Access rules
- strict teacher-workspace membership checks on every step
- no cross-workspace linking
- no unauthorized browsing/editing

9. Architecture rules
- prefer extending existing focused modules
- keep handlers thin
- introduce only the smallest reasonable FSM layer for UI navigation/editing
- avoid overengineering

10. Testing
Add or update focused tests to cover at least:
- teacher can browse/create workspace through `/teacher_content`
- teacher can browse/create topics
- entering create-topic or create-workspace replaces the current menu message instead of appending a duplicate menu
- back from prompt restores the previous menu in the same message
- topic screen renders the 3-message model correctly
- page navigation works for more than 25 items
- item prev/next navigation works
- field-by-field item editing works
- missing translations can be added later
- archive action works
- unauthorized access is rejected
- no FSM is used as source of truth for domain state

